Abstract
This report researches a protocol verification tool Squirrel Prover, which is based on the CCSA approach. Its usability has been explored through a series of case studies of the handshake protocol to verify secrecy property. The verification starts from a symbolic setting. Then extended to the computationally complete using IND-CCA assumption. Both of these two models are guaranteed by formal secrecy verification. Subsequently, there is an verification attempt on a real and ideal system using a computational model, but encounters challenges on name and index matching problems. Finally, all models are verified under post-quantum setting and achieve post-quantum soundness. These results indicate that Squirrel Prover is fully verified and achieves post-quantum security.
